description: Git commit conventions for this repo
alwaysApply: true
---

# Git commits

- Only commit when the user explicitly asks for it — never commit proactively.
- Write the subject as a single imperative sentence, capitalized, ending in a period, e.g.
  `Add Dotlan-style system plates and a Jump Range tool with pilot location tracking.` —
  no Conventional-Commit type prefixes (`feat:`, `fix:`, etc.), no issue numbers unless asked.
- Keep the subject to one line describing the net user-visible or architectural effect; add a
  blank line plus body paragraphs only if the change needs more explanation than the subject
  can carry.
- If the change touched `openspec/specs/`, make sure that update is part of the same commit as
  the code it documents (see the OpenSpec workflow rule) rather than a separate follow-up.
- Never stage build output or local caches: `bin/`, `obj/`, `release/`, `*.sqlite`, `.vs/`.
  These belong in `.gitignore`, not in a commit's diff — if you see them staged, something's
  wrong with `.gitignore` and it should be fixed instead of force-adding them.
- Before committing, run `git status` and `git diff --staged` and sanity-check that only the
  files relevant to the requested change are included.
